ight/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aPositioning consumer culture in Canada within a wider international context, Consuming Modernity explores the roots of modern Western mass culture between 1919 and 1945, when the female worker, student, and homemaker relied on new products to raise their standards of living and separate themselves from oppressive traditional attitudes. Mass-produced consumer products promised to free up women to pursue other interests shaped by marketing campaigns, advertisements, films, and radio shows. Concerns over fashion, personal hygiene, body image, and health reflected these new expectations. This volume is a fascinating look at how the forces of consumerism defined and redefined a generation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConsumption (Economics)xPolitical aspectsxHistoryy20th century. 0aConsumption (Economics)xPolitical aspectszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aConsumption (Economics)xSex differencesxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen consumersxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen in advertisingxHistoryy20th century. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAtchison, Devon Hansen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaillargeon, Denyse, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBelisle, Donica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlowen-Ledoux, Zoé, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEineigel, Susanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHall, Kristin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLight, Tracy Penny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiverant, Bettina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMalleck, Da